wherer
f is the risk‐free rate, andVis the covariance matrix of investment growth factors.3However, this estimator has two shortcomings. First, it is not an efficient estimator, since the estimation of the risk premiums is not incorporated in the GMM system. Second, and more important,Vneeds to be estimated, which gives rise to an error‐in‐variables problem in the calculation of the standard errors of λ’s.

Suppose that there is a change point at timeTπ. Using GMM, we can estimate the parameters for the sample between zero andTπ and the sample betweenTπ andT. We can impose the restriction that the parameters of the two samples are equal by also estimating the parameters for the whole sample period. To test whether this restriction holds, we can apply standard Wald, likelihood ratio, or Lagrange multiplier (LM) tests. The LM test is especially easy to perform because it uses only the restricted estimate, which is just the whole sample estimation that we already got from our previous GMM. To test whether there is a structural change in the time period betweenTπ1andTπ2, Andrews suggests using the
